alternatives.transcript: at the turn of the century American women were laced in Hamden tied in but they did have certain inalienable right the right to scrub floors the right to do laundry and the right to do windows but women wanted more they yearn to make a valuable contribution to society so women set their sights on a higher goal to reform America but while they fought for social changes from

labor laws to child welfare they realize they were neither free nor equal so with the courage of their convictions American women fought for the right to vote they marched and they demonstrated finally in 1916 they won it was the first step on the road to equality
in 1920 the first woman was elected to the US Senate and in 1933 the first woman join the u.s. cabinet
but those were small gains for a fortunate few most American women were relegated to housework or jobs with poor conditions and low pay until

women were finally given a chance to spread their wings Rosie the Riveter and millions of others spearhead of the war effort at home during WWII freed from sweatshops typewriters kitchens and department stores the women of America did the kind of work that was once Unthinkable for the fairer sex and what a job they did but after the war ended they were sent home to assume the traditional role of wife and mother

any wanted more they found their voice in the turbulent political climate of the 1960s and raise them even higher in the 1970s if they saw an equities they fought them if they wanted political power they work for it if they didn't want to wear bras they burn them now 20 years later in 1990 women have come a long way from their clothing styles to hairstyles from romance who financed from work

just how far have women come where do they still want to go this is the subject of the 1990 Virginia Slims opinion poll the nation's most comprehensive study of women's issues the results offer a 20-year perspective of women's opinions and changing roles in society most women today believe their lives have improved although many argue strongly that many changes still need to be made generally an overwhelming majority
D of women report that better jobs are available that their status and Society has improved and that their personal lives are relatively fulfilling

sixty-six percent of the women polled find their relationships with their children very fulfilling and 59% report that they are very satisfied with their relationships with friends 56% say that their relationship with the man in their life is fruitful and 48 percent believe their sex life is good however many women still find some areas of disappointment 33% are dissatisfied with their level of Education

33% are unhappy with their employer no surprise then that over a third dislike their jobs and only 18% are satisfied with the money they earn in fact Financial pressure creates stress and resentment causing problems in many marriages yet marriage remains an important priority for most American women so what makes for a good marriage 87% of women and 84 percent of men say it's that old standby

low Fidelity comes next 85% of women and 78% of men think faithfulness to a spouse is important women rape the ability to express feelings high with 84% women and men 76% but surprisingly enough a good sexual relationship ranked sixth on the list of priorities for a good marriage equal to having similar ideas on raising children however the Virginia Slims poll shows how

women are increasingly torn between work and home the fact is half of All American women now work most because they have to what would make their jobs more satisfying 55% say incentive programs 53% want better health benefits 42% want more flexible hours and for 31% an on-site daycare center would improve their lives

when asked who suffers most from time on the job forty-four percent of all women and 38 percent of men say the children 29 percent of women and men also report their marriage is affected yet the mommy track where a career woman receives fewer promotions and less pay in return for a more flexible schedule does not seem a viable option to the majority of women instead almost 70% look toward household and childcare help from men to make life better

unquestionably women in the workplace are on their way up but they feel that if they rise high enough they may very well bump their heads on an invisible glass ceiling that gives them a tantalizing view of the very top but keeps them a safe distance from it too many the corner office still seems as far away as it did to Rosie the Riveter yet attitudes towards success have definitely changed

of the four most respected women in 1990 only Barbara Bush with 41% is prominent because of her husband Oprah Winfrey British prime minister Margaret Thatcher and Robert Walters are respected because they made it on their own the Virginia Slims poll also examined the age-old battle between the Sexes while the number of couples living together quadrupled between 1970 and 1985 most still prefer marriage as a lifestyle

/ they don't think the institution of marriage is as strong as it used to be but as traditional roles change women's expectations are clearly shifting change continues to generate its natural fall out stress and uncertainty most women continue to yearn for a happy family a good marriage and a satisfying job with their greatest source of satisfaction still coming from the home

as we approach the new century we naturally look back at the one coming to a close while American women still have not achieved all that is possible One Thing Remains clear you've come a long way baby
